Logistic Regression¶

In [9]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import (
    accuracy_score,
    classification_report,
    confusion_matrix,
    roc_curve,
    auc,
    precision_recall_curve,
    f1_score,
)
from pprint import pprint


def present_results(results: dict):
    for key, value in results.items():
        print(f"\t{key:<16s}", end=":")
        pprint(value.mean() if hasattr(value, "mean") else value)


def evaluate_model(
    y_true,
    y_pred,
    y_prob,
    model_name,
    plots: bool = True,
) -> dict:
    print(f"\n{model_name} Evaluation:")
    print("-" * 40)

    # Classification report
    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))

    # Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Confusion Matrix:\n{cm}\n", 30 * "=")

    # ROC Auc
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, y_prob)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    # Precision & recall
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_prob)

    if plots:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)

        # ROC curve
        plt.plot(
            fpr,
            tpr,
            color="darkorange",
            lw=2,
            label=f"ROC curve (area = {roc_auc:.3f})",
        )
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color="navy", lw=2, linestyle="--")
        plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
        plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
        plt.title(f"ROC Curve - {model_name}")
        plt.legend(loc="lower right")

        # Precision-Recall Curve
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.plot(recall, precision, color="blue", lw=2)
        plt.xlabel("Recall")
        plt.ylabel("Precision")
        plt.title(f"Precision-Recall Curve - {model_name}")

    # Return F1 score, precision and recall
    return dict(f1_score=f1_score(y_true, y_pred), precision=precision, recall=recall)


def train_test_log_reg(
    data: pd.DataFrame,
    test_size: float = 0.1,
    random_state: int = 42,
) -> dict:
    X = data.drop(columns="Class")
    Y = data["Class"]
    print(f"{X.shape=}")
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X,
        Y,
        test_size=test_size,
        stratify=Y,
        random_state=random_state,
    )
    model = LogisticRegression(
        # class_weight='balanced',
        max_iter=1000,
        solver="liblinear",
        random_state=random_state,
    )
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    # Predict on training data
    x_train_prediction = model.predict(x_train)
    training_data_accuracy = accuracy_score(x_train_prediction, y_train)
    # Predict on test data
    x_test_prediction = model.predict(x_test)
    x_test_proba = model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    test_data_accuracy = accuracy_score(x_test_prediction, y_test)
    return dict(
        model=model,
        train_acc=training_data_accuracy,
        test_acc=test_data_accuracy,
        **evaluate_model(
            y_test,
            x_test_prediction,
            x_test_proba,
            "Logistic Regression",
        ),
    )

Autoencoder definitions¶

In [23]:
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
from tqdm.auto import tqdm
import numpy as np


class FraudDetector(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, encoded_features=6):
        super(FraudDetector, self).__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(input_dim, 20),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.BatchNorm1d(20),
            nn.Linear(20, 12),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(12, min(10, encoded_features)),
            nn.BatchNorm1d(encoded_features),
            nn.ReLU(),
        )

        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(min(10, encoded_features), 12),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(12, 20),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(20, input_dim),
        )

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.encoder(x)
        x = self.decoder(x)
        return x

    def fit(
        self,
        train_loader,
        criterion=nn.MSELoss(),
        optimizer=torch.optim.Adam,
        lr=0.001,
        num_epochs: int = 50,
        device: str = "cpu",
    ):
        optimizer = optimizer(self.parameters(), lr=lr)
        for epoch in tqdm(range(num_epochs), desc="Training epochs", position=0):
            total_loss = 0
            for batch in tqdm(
                train_loader,
                desc=f"Epoch {epoch+1} Batches",
                leave=False,
            ):
                batch = batch.to(device)

                # Forward pass
                reconstructed = self.forward(batch)
                loss = criterion(reconstructed, batch)

                # Backward pass
                optimizer.zero_grad()
                loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()

                total_loss += loss.item()

            tqdm.write(f"Epoch {epoch+1}, Loss: {total_loss/len(train_loader):.4f}")

    def predict(self, dataloader, device):
        errors = []
        with torch.no_grad():
            for batch in dataloader:
                batch = batch.to(device)
                reconstructed = self.forward(batch)
                error = torch.mean((reconstructed - batch) ** 2, dim=1)
                errors.extend(error.cpu().numpy())
        return np.array(errors)


class SmallFraudDetector(FraudDetector):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, encoded_features=6):
        super(FraudDetector, self).__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(input_dim, 16),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(16, min(10, encoded_features)),
        )

        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(min(10, encoded_features), 16),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(16, input_dim),
        )


device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve


ae_results = dict()
EPOCHS = 50

for model in models_to_run:
    for encoded_features in encoded_features_to_run:
        print(f"\n\nTraining {model.__name__} with {encoded_features} encoded features")
        model_instance = model(
            x_train_normal.shape[1],
            encoded_features=encoded_features,
        )
        model_instance.to(device)

        train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
            torch.tensor(x_train_normal.to_numpy(), dtype=torch.float32),
            batch_size=32,
            shuffle=True,
        )

        model_instance.fit(
            train_loader,
            lr=0.001,
            num_epochs=EPOCHS,
            device=device,
        )

        test_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
            torch.tensor(x_test.to_numpy(), dtype=torch.float32),
            batch_size=32,
            shuffle=False,
        )

        model_instance.eval()
        test_errors = model_instance.predict(test_loader, device)

        # Find optimal threshold using precision-recall curve
        precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, test_errors)
        f1_scores = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall + 1e-8)
        optimal_threshold = thresholds[f1_scores.argmax()]
        print(f"Optimal threshold: {optimal_threshold:.4f}")

        predictions = (test_errors > optimal_threshold).astype(int)
        model_name = f"{model.__name__}_{encoded_features}"
        print(model_name)
        print(classification_report(y_test, predictions))
        print(confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions))
        # tn, fp, fn, tp
        ae_results[model_name] = {"model": model_instance, "predictions": predictions}

    rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42)

    # undersampled_data = pd.concat([x_res, y_res], axis=1)

        torch.tensor(x_res.to_numpy(), dtype=torch.float32),
